<task id="015" project="spaarke-daily-update-service-r2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Abstract dependencies — props/parameters; remove solution-local imports (FR-07)</title>
    <phase>P2: Pattern D Hoist</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-hours>3</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>014</dependencies>
    <blocks>016</blocks>
    <tags>frontend, react, refactoring, typescript</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Tightens shared-lib boundary; prevents solution-coupling regressions</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Sequential after 014; consolidates surface API</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Per FR-07: every hoisted component and hook accepts abstracted dependencies as props/parameters: `authenticatedFetch`, `webApi`, `userId`, `tenantId`, optional callbacks (`onRateLimitError`, `onRecordOpen`). Grep of `@spaarke/daily-briefing-components/src/` must show ZERO imports from `src/solutions/LegalWorkspace`, `src/solutions/DailyBriefing`, or `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi`.
  </prompt>

  <role>SPAARKE platform developer. Expert in shared-lib boundary hygiene and dependency-injection patterns for hooks/components.</role>

  <goal>Zero solution-local imports inside the new package; all dependencies passed as props/parameters; clean architectural boundary.</goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Per FR-07: shared package must not import from any solution. This task closes any remaining transitive coupling left over from tasks 011–014.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.DailyBriefing.Components/src/</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-012">Shared package boundary; no consumer-direction imports.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">All hoisted components/hooks must accept `authenticatedFetch`, `webApi`, `userId`, `tenantId` + optional callbacks as props/parameters.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-012-shared-component-library.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-daily-update-service-r2/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-daily-update-service-r2/CLAUDE.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Run `grep -r "from '../../../../solutions" src/client/shared/Spaarke.DailyBriefing.Components/src/` (or equivalent path traversal) — list every violating import.</step>
    <step order="2">For each violation: refactor the import out by surfacing the dependency as a prop or hook parameter.</step>
    <step order="3">Update `types/index.ts` with shared dep-injection interfaces (e.g., `BriefingDependencies = { authenticatedFetch, webApi, userId, tenantId, onRateLimitError?, onRecordOpen? }`).</step>
    <step order="4">Verify components accept abstracted deps via composition (typically passed down from `DailyBriefingApp`).</step>
    <step order="5">Run `npm run build` on new package; verify build green.</step>
    <step order="6">Re-run grep — confirm zero solution-local imports remain.</step>
    <step order="7">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 015 status from 🔲 to ✅.</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="npm">Build TypeScript packages.</tool>
    <tool name="terminal">Grep + file ops.</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/client/shared/Spaarke.DailyBriefing.Components/src/types/index.ts</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`grep -r "solutions/" src/client/shared/Spaarke.DailyBriefing.Components/src/ --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx"` returns zero matches.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All component and hook signatures accept abstracted dependencies as props/parameters.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Build green on new package.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    This is hygiene work. If you find an unfixable solution-local coupling (e.g., a singleton from `LegalWorkspace`), surface in `notes/` and propose a hoist of that singleton.
  </notes>

